text: Dystonia 16 is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by early-onset progressive limb dystonia, laryngeal and oromandibular dystonia, and parkinsonism. It has a material basis in the homozygous mutation of the EIF2AK2 (PRKRA) gene on chromosome 2q31.

Paroxysmal nonkinesigenic dyskinesia 1 (PNKD) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the muscles. It is characterized by sudden and severe attacks of dystonic or choreathetotic movements, which are precipitated by stress, fatigue, alcohol consumption, menstruation, or caffeine intake. These movements can be very debilitating and cause significant discomfort for those affected by the disease.

PNKD is caused by mutations in the PNKD metallo-beta-lactamase domain containing gene, which is located on chromosome 2q35. The inheritance of this condition is autosomal dominant, meaning that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it.

There is no cure for PNKD, but medications and other therapies can be used to manage its symptoms. It is important for those affected by this condition to work with their healthcare providers to develop an individualized treatment plan that addresses their specific needs and helps them maintain the best possible quality of life.

Dystonia 27 is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by segmental dystonia that predominantly affects the craniocervical region and upper limbs, with onset in the first two decades of life. The condition has a material basis in compound heterozygous mutations in the collagen type VI alpha-3 gene located on chromosome 2q37.

Dystonia 23, also known as cervical dystonia, is a type of focal dystonia that affects the neck muscles and causes involuntary movements or spasms. It typically develops in adulthood, often in the fourth or fifth decade of life. The condition has a strong genetic component, with mutations in the CACNA1B gene on chromosome 9q34 being the most common cause of inheritance.

Dystonia 24, also known as generalized dystonia-24 or focal dystonia type 24, is a neurological disorder characterized by muscle stiffness and spasm. It is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means that it can be inherited from one parent to the other without being affected by the condition themselves.
Dystonia 24 affects the neck, laryngeal muscles, and muscles of the upper limbs, causing painful spasms and making it difficult for individuals to move their head, neck or arms freely. It is believed that the disorder has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, and this is supported by genetic research. Specifically, mutations in the ANO3 gene on chromosome 11p14 have been identified as a common cause of dystonia 24.

Episodic kinesigenic dyskinesia 1 (EKD) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that causes recurrent, brief episodes of involuntary movements triggered by sudden movements. It is also known as Paroxysmal kinesigenic choreoathetosis (PKCA). The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the proline-rich transmembrane protein 2 (PRRT2) gene, which is located on chromosome 16p11.

Episodic kinesigenic dyskinesia 2 (EKD2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the muscle tone and movement. It is characterized by recurrent brief involuntary hyperkinesias triggered by sudden movements, which have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of variation in the chromosome region 16q13-q22.1.

Dystonia 25, also known as generalized dystonia type 25 or GD25, is a form of primary dystonia characterized by muscle stiffness and contractions. It is an autosomal dominant disorder, which means that it can be inherited from one parent to the other. In Dystonia 25, there is a mutation in the GNAL gene on chromosome 18p11, which is responsible for causing this condition. Dystonia 25 affects multiple body parts, including the neck, larynx, and hands or arms. It can cause severe and disabling symptoms if not properly managed with medical treatment.

Dystonia 12 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects young adults, characterized by asymmetric dystonia and parkinsonism. The condition has a material basis in the heterozygous mutation of the gene encoding the alpha-3 subunit of the N,K-ATPase (ATP1A3) on chromosome 19q13.

x-linked dystonia-parkinsonism, also known as XDP or DYT3, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the muscles of the body. It is caused by an expansion in the gene coding for the protein alpha-dystroglycan, which results in excessive production of this glycoprotein. This leads to the formation of abnormal tissue and progressive muscle weakness, often causing symptoms similar to those of Parkinson's disease. XDP is inherited in an x-linked recessive pattern, meaning that a male with the condition will pass it on to all his daughters, while females who inherit the gene will pass it on to half their sons. There is no known cure for this disorder at present, but treatments can help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life.
torsion dystonia with onset in infancy is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Enhanced S cone syndrome is a rare retinal disease that affects the sensitivity of the photoreceptors in the eye. It is characterized by early onset night blindness, hypersensitivity to blue light, and sometimes more general retinal degeneration. The disease has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, which means that it is passed down through families and requires the transmission of two copies of the gene (one from each parent) for an individual to develop the condition. Enhanced S cone syndrome is caused by mutations in the nuclear receptor subfamily 2 group E member 3 gene (NR2E3), which is located on chromosome 15q23.

Wolcott Rallison syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems, including the liver and kidneys. It causes severe growth retardation, diabetes, and skeletal abnormalities such as dwarfism. Additionally, the condition can cause osteoporosis, hepatic dysfunction, and renal dysfunction. The syndrome is caused by mutations in the EIF2AK3 gene on chromosome 2p11.2. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that a person needs to inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Familial Cold Autoinflammatory Syndrome (FCAS) is a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by recurrent episodes of maculopapular skin rash triggered by exposure to cold associated with low-grade fever, general malaise, eye redness and arthralgia/myalgia. It is also known as FCAS. Is there anything else you would like to know about FCAS?

familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It's characterized by having a familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome that is due to the presence of a heterozygous mutation in the NLRP gene on chromosome 1q44.

familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome 2 is a type of familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome that has material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by heterozygous mutation in the NLRP12 gene on chromosome 19q13.

That is correct, Familial Cold Autoinflammatory Syndrome 4 (FCAS4) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that has material basis in some instances of heterozygous mutation in the NLRC4 gene on chromosome 2p22. It is characterized by episodic high fevers, urticaria-like rash and arthralgias starting at 2-3 months of age, often induced by cold exposure.

Fanconi syndrome, also known as Fanconi anemia, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by pancytopenia (a decrease in all three types of blood cells: red blood cells, white blood cells and platelets), immune deficiency, and an increased risk of developing certain types of cancer, particularly acute myeloid leukemia. The syndrome is named after Swiss pediatrician Theodor Fanconi who first described the disorder in 1927. It is caused by mutations in one of the genes that regulate blood cell formation, leading to bone marrow failure and the development of abnormal blood cells.

Fuhrmann syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bones. It is caused by a mutation in the WNT7A gene, which is located on chromosome 3p25. The symptoms of Fuhrmann syndrome include bowing of the femora (thighbones), aplasia or hypoplasia of the fibulae (the long bone that runs down the front of the leg), and poly-/oligo-/syndactyly (abnormal fusion of toes). The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.

Giant Axonal Neuropathy 1, also known as Charcot-Marie-Tooth Disease Type 2 (CMT2), is a genetic disorder that affects the peripheral nerves. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene, one from each parent, to develop the condition. The gene responsible for CMT2 is located on chromosome 16q23 and is called GIGAXONIN (GAN).
The disease is characterized by progressive motor and sensory peripheral neuropathy, which affects the nerves that run from the spine down to the limbs. It also affects the central nervous system, causing symptoms such as weakness, balance problems, and muscle stiffness.
One of the distinguishing features of CMT2 is the presence of giant axonal swellings, which are large, round structures filled with neurofilaments that can be seen in nerve biopsies. These swellings are believed to contribute to the degeneration of the nerves and the progression of the disease.
There is no cure for CMT2, but treatment options may include physical therapy, medications to manage pain and symptoms, and assistive devices such as wheelchairs or walkers.

Giant axonal neuropathy 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the peripheral nerves, causing distal sensory impairment and lower extremity muscle weakness. It also involves the accumulation of neurofilament in giant axonal swelling. This condition has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is caused by heterozygous mutations in the DDB1- and CUL4-associated factor 8 (DCAF8) gene on chromosome 1q23.

hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is a type of hypogonadism characterized by an impaired signaling by gonadotropin-releasing hormone. It has exact synonyms such as congenital idiopathic hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, hypogonadotropism, and isolated congenital gonadotropin deficiency.
hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 11 with or without anosmia is a form of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the gonads.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 12, also known as Kallmann syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder. It affects the development and functioning of the hypothalamus and pituitary gland, resulting in low levels of gonadotropins (luteinizing hormone and follicle-stimulating hormone) and decreased sex steroid production. This can lead to a range of symptoms, including delayed or absent puberty, small testes, infertility, and low libido. In some cases, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 12 can also be associated with anosmia (loss of the sense of smell).
hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 13 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal recessive disease.
hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 8 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 15 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is defined as a form of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that has a material basis in mutations in the HS6ST1 gene on chromosome 2q14, sometimes in association with mutations in other genes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 18, also known as Kallmann syndrome or isolated gonadotropin deficiency, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of reproductive organs and secondary sex characteristics. It can be inherited in an autosomal dominant or autosomal recessive manner.

Kallmann syndrome is characterized by hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, which means that the pituitary gland does not produce enough gonadotropins, such as luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH). This leads to a decrease in testicular production of testosterone and estradiol, resulting in the absence or delay of puberty.

In some cases, anosmia, or a lack of sense of smell, may also be present in individuals with Kallmann syndrome. The genetic cause of this disorder is due to mutations in the interleukin-17 receptor D (IL17RD) gene on chromosome 3p14.

Overall, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 18 is a rare condition that can have significant impacts on an individual's growth, development, and reproductive health. However, with proper medical care and support, those affected can lead fulfilling lives.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 4, also known as Kallmann syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disorder characterized by the absence of puberty due to a deficiency in gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) secretion from the hypothalamus and pituitary gland. It can also be associated with anosmia, or the loss of the sense of smell. The condition is caused by mutations in the PROK2 gene located on chromosome 3p13.

hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 7 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by the presence of a mutation in the GNRHR gene on chromosome 4q13, which can also be accompanied by a mutation in another gene. The condition is caused by a deficiency or absence of gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH), which leads to hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. It is important to note that this type of hypogonadism does not have anosmia, or the inability to smell, as a characteristic feature.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 17, also known as Kallmann syndrome, is a genetic disorder characterized by a lack of sexual development and the inability to sense smell. It is caused by mutations in specific genes on chromosome 5q31, including SPRY4. This condition can be inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit the disorder. In some cases, the disorder may also be caused by mutations in other genes or due to certain environmental factors. Treatment options for hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 17 typically involve hormone replacement therapy and/or surgical interventions to stimulate puberty and promote normal growth and development.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 16, also known as Kallmann syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by the absence or deficiency of sexual development due to insufficient gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) secretion from the hypothalamus and lack of maturation of the gonads, including the testes in males and ovaries in females. This condition can also be associated with anosmia or hyposmia, which refers to a reduced sense of smell. It is caused by mutations in the SEMA3A gene on chromosome 7, which leads to defects in the functioning of olfactory receptors and disrupts the normal development of the olfactory system.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism (22) with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by the presence of a mutation in the FEZF1 gene on chromosome 7q31. It is also referred to as Kallmann syndrome when it is accompanied by a lack of sense of smell (anosmia).
Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 20 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 2 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by the absence of puberty and the presence of low testosterone levels. It is caused by a genetic mutation in the FGFR1 gene, which is located on chromosome 8p11. The condition can also be associated with other genetic mutations, such as in the KALR1 gene. Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 2 with or without anosmia is a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, which is a medical condition characterized by abnormal functioning of the testes and/or ovaries. It can cause infertility, low sex drive, and other related symptoms.
hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 5 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, also known as Kallmann syndrome or idiopathic gonadotropin deficiency, is a type of autosomal dominant disorder. It occurs when the hypothalamus and pituitary gland do not produce enough gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) or luteinizing hormone (LH), which are necessary for normal sex development and functioning.

In some cases, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism can also be caused by a genetic mutation in the NELF gene on chromosome 9q34. This genetic defect can lead to abnormalities in the production of GnRH and LH, resulting in decreased sex steroid hormone levels and impaired reproductive function.

In addition to the genetic factors, other environmental and lifestyle factors, such as exposure to certain medications or chemicals, can also contribute to the development of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. However, in most cases, the underlying cause is not known.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 6, also known as Kallmann syndrome, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of reproductive organs in males. It is caused by a mutation in the FGF8 gene on chromosome 10q24, which is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. In some cases, it can also be associated with mutations in other genes. The main symptoms of this condition include delayed or absent puberty, small testicles, and a reduced sense of smell (anosmia). Treatment options may include hormone replacement therapy, gonadotropin therapy, and/or surgical interventions to help restore normal function.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 10, also known as Kallmann syndrome, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the gonads and sex steroid hormones. It is an autosomal recessive condition that is caused by mutations in the TAC3 gene on chromosome 12q13. This condition can cause infertility, a low sperm count, and a lack of development or underdevelopment of the testes and ovaries. Additionally, some individuals with this disorder may also experience anosmia, or a loss of sense of smell.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 19, also known as Kallmann syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the absence or reduced function of the gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) system. This can result in problems with the development and production of sex hormones such as testosterone and estrogen, leading to underdeveloped reproductive organs and infertility.

In some cases, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 19 can also be accompanied by anosmia, or the inability to smell certain odors. However, this is not always present, and the condition can still occur without it. The disease is caused by a mutation in the DUSP6 gene on chromosome 12q22, which is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner.

It's important to note that while hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 19 can cause infertility, there are treatments available such as gonadotropin replacement therapy, hormone replacement therapy, and other assisted reproductive technologies like in vitro fertilization (IVF).

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 23 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by the absence or reduced function of luteinizing hormone (LH), which is necessary for normal development and maintenance of male sex organs. It is also known as Kallmann syndrome, and it can be inherited from one's parents if both of them are carriers of the gene mutation that causes this condition. Symptoms may include low testosterone levels, small or undescended testes, sparse beard and body hair, and infertility. It is important to consult with a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment options.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 3 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the absence of puberty due to a lack of gonadotropin secretion from the pituitary gland. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PROKR2 gene on chromosome 20p12, and sometimes in association with mutations in other genes as well.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 21 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the lack of puberty and small testes. It is caused by mutations in the FLRT3 gene on chromosome 20, and it can also be associated with other genetic changes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 1 with or without anosmia is a type of x-linked recessive disease that is characterized by the failure of the pituitary gland to produce enough gonadotropins, which are hormones that stimulate testicular function and sperm production. This condition can result in low levels of testosterone and other sex steroids, as well as a reduced or absent sense of smell (anosmia). It is caused by mutations in the KAL1 gene on chromosome Xp22.3, which encodes a protein involved in the production of gonadotropins. In some cases, additional mutations in another gene may also be present. This condition can cause various symptoms, including low testosterone levels, infertility, small testes, and a reduced sense of smell. It is important to note that this condition is rare and most common in males.

Autosomal dominant macrothrombocytopenia, also known as TUBB1-related thrombocytopenia, is a type of thrombocytopenia characterized by low platelet count, normal platelet aggregation and having the inheritance pattern of autosomal dominant. It is caused by mutations in the TUBB1 gene on chromosome 20q13.3.

Huntington's disease like 1 (HDL1) is a type of prion disease characterized by symptoms that mimic those of Huntington's disease, including chorea, behavioral and psychiatric disturbances, and dementia. It is caused by the inheritance of an extra copy of a specific gene called PRNP on chromosome 20p13. The condition is also known as autosomal dominant Huntington-like neurodegenerative disorder (HDALND) or early-onset prion disease with prominent psychiatric features.

Huntington disease-like 2 (HDL2) is a type of neurodegenerative disease that affects the brain and spinal cord. It causes involuntary movements, abnormalities of voluntary movements, psychiatric symptoms, weight loss, and dementia. The onset of HDL2 occurs in the fourth decade, and it leads to death about 20 years after disease onset. This condition is caused by an autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous expansion of a CAG/CTG repeat in the junctophilin-3 gene (JPH3) located on chromosome 16q24. It is also known as Huntington's disease like 2, and it has the same symptoms as Huntington's disease but with a different cause.
Autosomal recessive hypercholesterolemia is a type of familial hypercholesterolemia.

Tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4)-deficient hyperphenylalaninemia is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by hyperphenylalaninemia, depletion of the neurotransmitters dopamine and serotonin, and progressive cognitive and motor deficits. It has material basis in mutations in the gene encoding 6-pyruvoyl-tetrahydropterin synthase (PTS) on chromosome 11q23.1. This condition has exact synonyms such as 6-pyruvoyl-tetrahydropterin synthase deficiency, HPABH4A, PTS deficiency, and hyperphenylalaninemia due to 6-pyruvoyltetrahydropterin synthase deficiency.

Autosomal dominant hypocalcemia 1 is a genetic disorder where the calcium levels in the blood are low due to a mutation in the CASR gene on chromosome 3q21. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a single copy of the mutated gene is enough for the condition to develop. This disorder can lead to various health issues if left untreated, including muscle cramps and spasms, seizures, and abnormal heart rhythms. Treatment typically involves supplementing with calcium and vitamin D to help maintain normal levels of these minerals in the body.

Autosomal dominant hypocalcemia type 2, also known as autosomal dominant hypocalcemia type 2 or HYPOC2, is a condition that is characterized by low levels of calcium in the blood. This condition is caused by a mutation in the GNA11 gene on chromosome 19p13. It is considered to be an autosomal dominant disorder, which means that it can be passed down through families and tends to affect multiple family members. Symptoms of this condition may include weakness, muscle cramps, seizures, and numbness or tingling in the hands and feet. It is important for individuals with this condition to work closely with their healthcare provider to manage their calcium levels and prevent complications.

Autosomal dominant hypocalcemia is a condition characterized by low levels of calcium in the blood, which is due to the inheritance of a specific gene from one or both parents. This type of inheritance means that if one parent has the gene, there's a 50% chance that their child will inherit it and develop the condition.

Yes, immune dysregulation polyendocrinopathy enteropathy x linked syndrome is a type of X-linked recessive disease that is characterized by onset in infancy of refractory diarrhea, endocrinopathies, type 1 diabetes mellitus, and dermatitis. It has exact synonyms such as autoimmune enteropathy type 1, DMSD, IDDM-secretory diarrhea syndrome, IPEX, X-linked autoimmunity-allergic dysregulation syndrome, XPID, and various other names. It is also known as immunodeficiency, polyendocrinopathy, and enteropathy, X-linked.

PCWH Syndrome is also known as Neurologic Waardenburg-Shah Syndrome and is characterized by a combination of features including sensorineural hearing loss, pigmentary abnormalities, Hirschsprung disease, neonatal hypotonia, intellectual deficit, nystagmus, progressive spasticity, ataxia, and epilepsy. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation of the SRY-box 10 (SOX10) gene on chromosome 22q13.

Nasu Hakola disease is a rare, autosomal recessive genetic disorder characterized by progressive presenile dementia and recurrent bone fractures due to polycystic osseous lesions of the lower and upper extremities. The condition has a material basis in homozygous mutations in either the TYRO protein tyrosine kinase binding protein (TYROBP) gene on chromosome 19q13 or the triggering receptor expressed on myeloid cells 2 (TREM2) gene on chromosome 6p21. The disease is also known by its synonyms: polycystic lipomembranous osteodysplasia with sclerosing leukoencephalopathy, presenile dementia with bone cysts, progressive dementia with lipomembranous polycystic osteodysplasia; brain-bone-fat disease.

Riddle syndrome, also known as RNF168 deficiency or Radiosensitivity-immunodeficiency-dysmorphic features-learning difficulties syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple systems in the body. It is characterized by increased sensitivity to radiation exposure (radiosensitivity), immune system dysfunction, mild motor control and learning difficulties, facial dysmorphism, and short stature. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ring finger protein 168 (RNF168) gene on chromosome 3q29.

Sorsby's fundus dystrophy, also known as SFD or hemorrhagic macular dystrophy, is a type of autosomal dominant retinal disease. It is characterized by the progressive loss of central vision due to macular disease, with peripheral visual loss occurring in late life. This condition has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is caused by mutations in the TIMP3 gene on chromosome 22q12. It is also synonymous with pseudoinflammatory fundus dystrophy of Sorsby.

Spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy 1, also known as SCAN1, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by the inheritance of spinocerebellar ataxia and peripheral neuropathy due to homozygosity for a mutation in the TDP1 gene on chromosome 14q32.11. It is important to note that this condition has a material basis in genetics, specifically autosomal recessive inheritance of spinocerebellar ataxia and peripheral neuropathy resulting from mutations in the TDP1 gene.

Spondylocarpotarsal synostosis (SCT) is a rare autosomal recessive genetic disorder that affects bone development. It causes the vertebrae in the spine to fuse prematurely, resulting in abnormalities such as a short trunk, scoliosis, and other skeletal issues. The condition also involves the fusion of carpal and tarsal bones in the hands and feet, which can result in clubfoot and other deformations. SCT typically affects infants and children and is often diagnosed at birth or during early childhood. It is caused by mutations in the filamin B (FLNB) gene on chromosome 3p14.3.

Thiamine responsive megaloblastic anemia syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by megaloblastic anemia, non-type I diabetes mellitus, and sensorineural deafness. It is responsive to high doses of thiamine, and has been linked to homozygous mutation in the solute carrier family 19 member 2 (SLC19A2) gene on chromosome 1q24. The syndrome also known as Rogers Syndrome, THMD1, TRMA, thiamine metabolism dysfunction syndrome 1 and thiamine-responsive anemia syndrome with diabetes mellitus and sensorineural deafness.

Congenital amegakaryocytic thrombocytopenia is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by a severe reduction in megakaryocyte and platelet numbers. It has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the myeloproliferative leukemia virus oncogene (MPL) on chromosome 1p34. It is also known as CAMT, and can present with symptoms of thrombocytopenia, including purpura.

Ankyloblepharon Ectodermal Defects Cleft Lip Palate Syndrome, also known as AEC Syndrome or Hay-Wells Syndrome, is a genetic condition that affects the development of certain tissues and organs. It is characterized by ankyloblepharon (a thickening of the skin around the eyes), filiform adnatum (a hair-like structure in the ear), cleft lip and palate, and other ectodermal abnormalities.

The syndrome is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the gene can be passed down from one generation to another. The mutation responsible for this condition occurs on chromosome 3q27 and affects the tumor protein p63 (TP63).

AEC Syndrome is also known as ankyloblepharon-ectodermal defects-cleft lip and palate syndrome, which accurately describes the condition. It's important to note that there might be other synonyms for this syndrome, but these are some of the most commonly used terms in medical literature.

Hereditary neutrophilia is a type of leukocyte disease that is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance and lifelong elevated neutrophil counts primarily consisting of segmented neutrophils. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the colony stimulating factor 3 receptor (CSF3R) gene on chromosome 1p34.

Aromatase excess syndrome, also known as AEXS or familial hyperestrogenism, is a reproductive system disease characterized by increased extraglandular aromatization of steroids resulting in heterosexual precocity in males and isosexual precocity in females. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, which involves the fusion of the aromatase gene (CYP19A1) with various partners, leading to an increase in the activity of the CYP19A1 gene. The exact synonyms for Aromatase excess syndrome include increased aromatase activity and hereditary prepubertal gynecomastia.

Aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that affects the production of neurotransmitters such as serotonin and dopamine. It causes a range of symptoms, including hypotonia (low muscle tone), hypokinesia (difficulty moving), ptosis (drooping eyelids), oculogyric crises (involuntary nystagmus of the eyes), and signs of autonomic dysfunction. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that it requires the inheritance of two copies of the gene for its expression. This results from mutations in the dopa decarboxylase gene (DDC) located on chromosome 7p12.

Neurogenic type arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 2 is a specific condition that affects the joints and muscles, specifically causing congenital contractures at the elbows and knees. It's caused by a mutation in the ERGIC1 gene on chromosome 5q35, which is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. Additionally, it is characterized by myopathy, absence of muscle spindles, congenital heart disease, and spinal motor neuron depletion.

Brain small vessel disease 1 is a type of autosomal dominant brain disorder characterized by fragile blood vessels in the brain and other symptoms such as leukoencephalopathy, increased risk of stroke, seizure, migraine, and in some cases Axenfeld-Riegar anomaly. It has an exact synonym BSVD1 and is also known as COL4A1-related brain small vessel disease with hemorrhage, familial vascular leukoencephalopathy, retinal arteriolar tortuosity-infantile hemiparesis-autosomal dominant leukoencephalopathy syndrome, and autosomal dominant retinal arteriolar tortuosity, infantile hemiparesis, and leukencephalopathy. It also has synonyms such as brain small vessel disease with Axenfeld-Riegar anomaly, brain small vessel disease with or without ocular anomalies, and leukoencephalopathy with Axenfeld-Riegar anomaly.

Branched Chain Keto Acid Dehydrogenase Kinase Deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the metabolism of amino acids. It causes a deficiency in the enzyme Branched Chain Keto Acid Dehydrogenase, which leads to an accumulation of three specific amino acids (leucine, isoleucine and valine). This can result in various symptoms such as autism, epilepsy, intellectual disability and reduced levels of these three amino acids. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the Branched Chain Keto Acid Dehydrogenase Kinase gene (BCKDK) on chromosome 16p11.

The term "camptodactyly arthropathy coxa vara pericarditis syndrome" refers to a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple joints in the body, particularly the fingers and wrists. It is characterized by camptodactyly (bent finger), non-inflammatory arthropathy (joint disease without inflammation), coxa vara (bending of the knee cap backwards), and pericarditis or pleural effusion (inflammation of the lining surrounding the heart or buildup of fluid around the lungs). The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that it requires two copies of the gene for the disease to develop. It has also been referred to as CACP, CAP, Jacobs syndrome, and PAC syndrome.

Carvajal syndrome, also known as Naxos disease, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by dilated cardiomyopathy, woolly hair (pili trichus), and keratoderma. It is caused by a homozygous mutation in the desmoplakin gene on chromosome 6p24. The exact synonyms for Carvajal syndrome include dilated cardiomyopathy with woolly hair and keratoderma, palmoplantar keratoderma with left ventricular cardiomyopathy and woolly hair, and DCWHK.

Carnitine palmitoyltransferase I deficiency is a type of lipid metabolism disorder that results from impaired mitochondrial oxidation of long-chain fatty acids in the liver and kidneys. This can lead to episodes of illness or fasting-induced hypoketotic hypoglycemia, which is a condition characterized by low blood sugar levels due to insufficient amounts of ketones being produced. Carnitine palmitoyltransferase I deficiency is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. Some common synonyms for carnitine palmitoyltransferase I deficiency include CPT I deficiency, CPT1A deficiency, L-CPT1 deficiency, and hepatic CPT deficiency type I.

Cortical dysplasia focal epilepsy syndrome (CDFE) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the brain. It is also known as CDFE syndrome, CDFES, PTHSL1, and Pitt-Hopkins-like syndrome-1.

cortisone reductase deficiency is a condition in which the body is unable to convert cortisone into cortisol. Cortisol is an important hormone that helps regulate blood sugar levels and the body's response to stress. When someone has cortisone reductase deficiency, they may experience symptoms such as weight loss, fatigue, and a weakened immune system. It is caused by a genetic mutation that affects the enzyme that converts cortisone into cortisol. Treatment typically involves hormone replacement therapy to supplement the body with the necessary cortisol.

Cortisone reductase deficiency 2 (CORTRD2) is a type of autosomal dominant disorder. It is caused by the lack of an enzyme called 11-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase, which results in the body not being able to produce cortisol properly. This leads to ACTH-mediated adrenal hyperandrogenism and has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of heterozygous mutation in the 11-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase type I (HSD11B1) gene on chromosome 1q32. The exact synonym for CORTRD2 is cortisone reductase deficiency 2.

Cortisone reductase deficiency 1 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the adrenal gland, which is responsible for producing cortisol. Cortisol is a hormone that helps regulate blood sugar levels and other bodily functions. People with this condition have difficulty regenerating cortisol due to a deficiency in the enzyme 11-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase, which requires NADPH for its functioning. This leads to ACTH-mediated adrenal hyperandrogenism, causing symptoms such as low blood sugar levels, weight loss, and other health problems.
Cortisone reductase deficiency 1 is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. It is caused by mutations in the H6PD gene, located on chromosome 1p36.
While cortisone reductase deficiency 1 is rare, it can have a significant impact on a person's health and well-being if left untreated. Treatment typically involves medications to manage symptoms and prevent complications, such as hypoglycemia. With proper medical care, people with cortisone reductase deficiency 1 can lead normal lives.

Cystathioninuria is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by elevated plasma and urinary cystathionine levels due to mutations in the gene encoding cystathionine gamma-lyase (CTH) on chromosome 1p31. Donnai-Barrow syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects many organ systems in the body. It is characterized by severe congenital diaphragmatic hernia, exomphalos (extreme outward protrusion of the abdomen), hypertelorism (large spacing between the eyes), myopia (nearsightedness), sensorineural hearing loss, and proteinuria (abnormal protein in the urine). Additionally, individuals with this condition often have intellectual disability. The syndrome is caused by mutations in the LDL receptor-related protein 2 gene (LRP2) located on chromosome 2q31. It has been referred to by several other names, including facio-oculo-acoustico-renal syndrome and syndrome of ocular and facial anomalies, telecanthus and deafness.

Dopamine beta hydroxylase deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that affects the nervous system. It occurs due to an inherited mutation in the DBH gene, which results in decreased activity of dopamine beta-hydroxylase enzyme, leading to impaired autonomic noradrenergic neurotransmission and various symptoms such as severely decreased norepinephrine levels, orthostatic hypotension, ptosis (drooping eyelids), nasal stuffiness, and delayed eye opening. This disorder has a basis in structural variants of the DBH gene and is located in the nervous system, particularly affecting the brainstem and spinal cord. It can be diagnosed through genetic testing and treated with medications that help increase norepinephrine levels and prevent complications such as low blood pressure when standing up.

3 methylglutaconic aciduria type 5 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of amino acids in the body. It is caused by a mutation in the DNAJC19 gene located on chromosome 3q26. The disorder leads to an accumulation of 3-methylglutaconic acid, which can cause various symptoms such as developmental delays, ataxia, and cardiomyopathy. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. There are other types of 3-methylglutaconic aciduria, but type 5 is the most severe and can lead to life-threatening complications if left untreated.
3-Methylglutaconic aciduria with deafness, encephalopathy and Leigh-like syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

This is a rare metabolic disorder that affects the body's ability to process amino acids, leading to an accumulation of 3-methylglutaconic acid. It is caused by mutations in the AUH gene located on chromosome 9q22. The condition can cause neurological symptoms and physical developmental delay, and can be diagnosed through newborn screening or genetic testing. Treatment may include dietary modifications, supplements, and enzyme replacement therapy.
3-methylglutaconic aciduria with cataracts, neurologic involvement, and neutropenia is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

3 methylglutaconic aciduria type 3 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of 3-methylglutarconic acid. It is caused by mutations in the OPA3 gene, which is located on the X chromosome. The disorder can cause vision loss and other neurological symptoms, such as chorea, spastic paraplegia, and optic atrophy. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. There is no cure for 3 methylglutaconic aciduria type 3, but early diagnosis and management can help slow down its progression and improve quality of life.

Leber congenital amaurosis 9 (LCA9) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the retina, causing vision loss. It is caused by mutations in the NMNAT1 gene on chromosome 1p36. It has exact synonym LCA9.

3 methylglutaconic aciduria type 4 is a form of the rare metabolic disorder 3-methylglutaconic aciduria. It is characterized by intermittent or mild urinary excretion of 3-methylglutaconic acid, which is a breakdown product of glutamate and glutamine. This type of aciduria affects the metabolism of amino acids, specifically glutamate and glutamine. It is one of five types of 3-methylglutaconic aciduria, each with varying severity and symptoms.
It is important to note that this disorder can cause neurological problems in severe cases, particularly in infancy and childhood. These issues may include developmental delays, seizures, and other complications. Early diagnosis and proper management are crucial for the well-being of individuals with 3 methylglutaconic aciduria type 4.

Achromatopsia 2, also known as RMCH2 or rod monochromatism 2, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the vision. It is caused by mutations in the CNGA3 gene on chromosome 2q11. The condition results in difficulty seeing certain colors and reduced visual acuity.

Achromatopsia 3 is a genetic disorder that affects the ability to see color. It is one of several forms of achromatopsia, which are inherited vision disorders that cause total color blindness. Achromatopsia 3 is caused by mutations in the CNGB3 gene on chromosome 8q2. The condition can also be referred to by other names such as Pingelapese blindness, rod monochromacy 1, and ACHM1 or ACHM3.

Achromatopsia 7, also known as ACHM7, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the retina of the eye and causes difficulty in seeing colors. It is caused by mutations in the ATF6 gene, which is located on chromosome 1q23. This type of achromatopsia is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. Symptoms typically begin in childhood and can include reduced color vision, sensitivity to light, and difficulty adapting to changing light conditions. There is no cure for achromatopsia 7, but treatment may include glasses, contact lenses, and other visual aids to help improve vision and reduce symptoms.

Achromatopsia 4, also known as achromatopsia 4, is a type of color blindness caused by mutations in the GNAT2 gene. It is characterized by difficulty seeing colors and is often accompanied by other vision problems such as reduced visual acuity and sensitivity to light.

Advanced sleep phase syndrome 1 (ASPS1) is a specific type of circadian rhythm disorder characterized by an early wake-up time, typically between 2-4am, and difficulty falling asleep later in the evening. It is caused by mutations in the PER2 gene on chromosome 2q37, which is responsible for regulating the production of melatonin, a hormone that helps control sleep-wake cycles. ASPS1 can be inherited or occur spontaneously and often runs in families.
ASPS1 shares similarities with familial advanced sleep phase syndrome (FASPS) but has a different genetic background. FASPS is caused by mutations in the CLOCK gene on chromosome 7. While both disorders result in an early wake-up time, individuals with ASPS1 tend to have more difficulty falling asleep later in the evening compared to those with FASPS.
It's important to note that while ASPS1 can be a genetic disorder, it does not necessarily mean that everyone with the condition will experience the same symptoms or severity. Other factors such as age, lifestyle, and overall health may also play a role in determining an individual's circadian rhythm and sleep patterns.

Advanced sleep phase syndrome 2, also known as FASPS2 or familial advanced sleep phase syndrome 2, is a type of advanced sleep phase syndrome that is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CSNK1D gene on chromosome 17q25.

Advanced Sleep Phase Syndrome 3 (ASPS3) is a type of circadian rhythm sleep disorder characterized by an advanced sleep-wake cycle. It is caused by mutations in the PER3 gene on chromosome 1p36.23, which leads to an earlier timing of the circadian clock. Individuals with ASPS3 tend to go to bed and wake up significantly earlier than the average population, often in the range of 7:00-8:30 am. The disorder can cause difficulties with work or school schedules, sleep deprivation, and social interactions. Treatment options may include adjusting sleep and wake times to the individual's natural circadian rhythm, light therapy, medications such as melatonin or modafinil, and cognitive behavioral therapy for insomnia (CBT-I).

Age-related macular degeneration 1 (ARMD1) is a type of age-related macular degeneration characterized by polymorphism in the hemicentin gene (HMCN1) located on chromosome 1q25.3-q31.1. This genetic variation is associated with the development and progression of the disease, which can lead to vision loss and blindness. ARMD1 is also known as age-related maculopathy 1 (ARM1) and has been identified as a risk factor for age-related macular degeneration, the most common cause of vision loss in people over the age of 50. It's essential to maintain good eye health through regular checkups and appropriate lifestyle changes to reduce the risk of developing this condition.

Age-related macular degeneration 2 (ARMD2) is a type of age-related macular degeneration, characterized by the presence of atrophic changes in the retinal pigment epithelium and drusen. It is caused by genetic variations in the ABCA4 gene on chromosome 1p22. ARMD2 has the same symptoms as age-related macular degeneration but with different causes.

Leber congenital amaurosis 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by night blindness, some transient improvement in vision, and eventual progressive visual loss. It has material basis in mutation in the RPE65 gene on chromosome 1.

Age-related macular degeneration 4 (ARMD4), also known as advanced age-related macular degeneration, is a type of age-related macular degeneration characterized by the presence of drusen and geographic atrophy in both eyes. It is caused by variations in the CFH gene on chromosome 1q31. This condition has the exact synonym ARMD4.

Age-related macular degeneration 6 (ARMD6) is a type of age-related macular degeneration caused by a heterozygous mutation in the RAXL1 gene on chromosome 19p13. It has been assigned an official name and is also known as ARMD6.

Age-related macular degeneration 7 (ARMD7) is a type of age-related macular degeneration that is caused by a variation in the HTRA1 gene on chromosome 10q26. This condition has been defined and is known as ARMD7. It has an exact synonym of ARMD7, which means it refers to the same disease entity.

Age-related macular degeneration 8 (ARMD8), also known as Locus Candidatus ARMS2, is a type of age-related macular degeneration characterized by the presence of a mutation in the ARMS2 gene. This genetic variation has been linked to an increased risk of developing age-related macular degeneration, particularly in individuals with a family history of the condition. ARMD8 represents a specific subtype of age-related macular degeneration that is associated with genetic factors, offering insights into the underlying mechanisms and potential treatments for this prevalent eye disease.

Age-related macular degeneration (AMD) is a common eye condition that affects the central part of the retina, called the macula. It is also known as age-related macular degeneration 9, which refers to a specific type of AMD conferred by variation in the C3 gene on chromosome 19p13.

Age-related macular degeneration can cause vision loss and blindness if left untreated. There are two main types of AMD: dry (atrophic) and wet (neovascular or exudative). Dry AMD is more common and usually affects both eyes, while wet AMD tends to affect only one eye.

Symptoms of AMD may include a blurred or distorted vision, difficulty recognizing faces, dark spots or shadowy areas in the center of vision, and visual hallucinations. In more advanced stages, people with AMD may have trouble reading, driving, or performing other activities that require clear vision.

Treatment options for AMD include lifestyle changes such as quitting smoking, eating a balanced diet rich in antioxidants and omega-3 fatty acids, and regular exercise. In some cases, prescription eye drops or supplements may also be recommended to slow down the progression of AMD.

It is important to have regular eye exams to detect early signs of AMD and begin treatment promptly, as vision loss from AMD cannot be fully reversed. Early detection can help maintain better vision and prevent more severe vision loss in the future.

Age-related macular degeneration (ARMD) is a common eye disease that affects the macula, which is responsible for sharp central vision. There are two main types of ARMD: dry and wet. Dry ARMD occurs when the body produces deposits underneath the retina, leading to gradual loss of vision. Wet ARMD, on the other hand, happens when abnormal blood vessels grow underneath the retina, causing a sudden decline in vision.

ARMD is more common in individuals over 60 years of age and can lead to legal blindness if left untreated. The risk factors for developing ARMD include age, genetics, smoking, high blood pressure, obesity, and a family history of the disease. Early detection and treatment are crucial in managing this condition and preserving vision.

There is currently no cure for ARMD, but various treatments can help slow down its progression. In some cases, eye vitamins containing antioxidants like vitamin C, vitamin E, and zinc may be recommended to reduce the risk of developing ARMD. Laser therapy or photodynamic therapy may also be used to destroy abnormal blood vessels in wet ARMD.

It is important for individuals with a family history of ARMD or other risk factors to schedule regular eye exams with an ophthalmologist, who can monitor their vision and recommend appropriate treatments if necessary.

Age-related macular degeneration 11 (ARMD11) is a specific type of age-related macular degeneration characterized by genetic variations in the CST3 gene located on chromosome 20p11. It is also known as age-related macular degeneration conferred by variation in the CST3 gene.

Age-related macular degeneration (AMD) is a prevalent eye condition that affects the macula, which is responsible for sharp central vision. It occurs as people age and can lead to vision loss. There are two main types of AMD: dry and wet. Dry AMD is more common and results from the breakdown of light-sensitive cells in the macula, while wet AMD is less common and occurs when abnormal blood vessels grow underneath the retina and leak fluid.
There are several genetic factors that contribute to the development of AMD, including mutations in various genes. One such gene is CX3CR1, which is located on chromosome 3p22. Mutations in this gene have been linked to age-related macular degeneration type 12 (AMD12), also known as "dry" AMD.
In summary, AMD is a common eye condition that affects the macula and can lead to vision loss. It has two main types: dry and wet, with mutations in the CX3CR1 gene being associated with dry AMD specifically.

Age-related macular degeneration (AMD) is a common eye condition that affects the macula, which is responsible for sharp central vision. There are two main types of AMD: dry (atrophic) and wet (neovascular or exudative). Dry AMD occurs when the macula becomes thinner and less able to support blood vessels, causing it to dry out and die. Wet AMD is more severe and occurs when abnormal blood vessels grow under the retina, leaking blood and fluid that can cause rapid vision loss.

AMD typically affects people over 60 years of age and is more common in Caucasians than in other ethnic groups. It is caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors, with genetics playing a larger role in the development of AMD than previously thought. Researchers have identified several genes associated with an increased risk of developing AMD, including complement factor H (CFH), age-related maculopathy susceptibility 2 (APOE), and complement component 3 (C3).

There is no cure for dry AMD, but treatments can slow its progression and improve vision. For wet AMD, treatment options include laser therapy, photodynamic therapy, intravitreal injection of anti-VEGF drugs, or surgery to remove the abnormal vessels. Preventive measures such as a healthy diet rich in fruits and vegetables, regular exercise, quitting smoking, and wearing sunglasses can help reduce the risk of developing AMD.

Age-related macular degeneration (AMD) is a common eye disease that affects the macula, which is the central part of the retina responsible for sharp, detailed vision. There are two main forms of AMD: dry (atrophic) and wet (neovascular or exudative). Dry AMD occurs when the body produces harmful free radicals that damage the macula, while wet AMD occurs when abnormal blood vessels grow under the retina and leak fluid.

AMD is an age-related condition, with most people developing it after the age of 50. However, some people may experience symptoms in their 40s or earlier. Risk factors for AMD include age, family history, smoking, high blood pressure, obesity, and exposure to sunlight.

Symptoms of AMD can include blurred vision, dark spots or lines in the field of vision, difficulty recognizing faces, and a decline in overall vision. Early detection and treatment are crucial for managing the condition and preserving sight. Treatment options may include medication to slow the progression of the disease, laser therapy to destroy abnormal blood vessels, or surgery in some cases.

It is important to note that AMD can cause significant vision loss if left untreated, so it is crucial for individuals to visit their eye doctor regularly and follow recommended guidelines for a healthy lifestyle to reduce the risk of developing this condition.

ARMD15 refers to Age-Related Macular Degeneration, specifically the 15th subtype. It is characterized by a mutation in the C9 gene on chromosome 5p13. Age-related macular degeneration 5 (AMD5) is a type of age-related macular degeneration. AMD5 is caused by a mutation in the ERCC6 gene, which is located on chromosome 10q11. The condition has been referred to as ARMD5 due to its association with this specific genetic mutation. Alpha thalassemia intellectual disability syndrome type 1 is a genetic condition where there is a deletion in the chromosome 16 that involves several genes, including the alpha-1 (HBA1) and alpha-2 (HBA2) genes. Hemoglobin H disease (also known as hemoglobin H or alpha-thalassemia intermedia) is a type of alpha thalassemia caused by the deletion or mutation of one or both of the genes responsible for producing the alpha globin chains in hemoglobin. This results in the production of abnormal or less functional hemoglobin molecules, leading to anemia and other health problems.
Hemoglobin H disease can be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. It is also sometimes caused by a deletion or mutation in one of the genes responsible for producing the beta globin chains in hemoglobin.
Treatment options for hemoglobin H disease depend on the severity of the anemia and other symptoms, but may include blood transfusions to increase the level of healthy red blood cells, iron chelation therapy to remove excess iron from the body, and bone marrow transplantation in some cases.

Autosomal dominant Alport syndrome is a type of genetic disorder that affects the kidneys and hearing. It is caused by mutations in the COL4A3 gene, which is located on the X chromosome. The condition is characterized by progressive kidney disease and sensorineural deafness.

Autosomal recessive Alport syndrome is a type of Alport syndrome, which is a genetic disorder that affects the kidneys and the ears. The inheritance pattern for this condition is autosomal recessive, meaning that both copies of the gene need to be inherited from different affected individuals (i.e., homozygous or compound heterozygous) for the disorder to be expressed.

Alzheimer's disease is a neurological disorder that affects memory, thinking, and behavior. It is the most common cause of dementia in older adults. Alzheimer's disease is characterized by the buildup of abnormal protein deposits in the brain, which leads to the death of brain cells and shrinkage of brain tissue. There are three main types of Alzheimer's disease: early-onset, late-onset, and familial. Early-onset Alzheimer's disease typically affects people under 65 years of age, while late-onset Alzheimer's disease usually begins after the age of 65. Familial Alzheimer's disease is caused by specific gene mutations that are passed down through families. In addition to protein deposits, there is evidence to suggest that inflammation and changes in metabolism also play a role in the progression of the disease. Treatments for Alzheimer's disease focus on managing symptoms and improving quality of life. There is no cure for Alzheimer's disease at this time, but ongoing research is exploring potential treatments and therapies that may help slow its progression or even reverse the damage in some cases.

Alzheimer's disease type 16, also known as late-onset Alzheimer's, is a form of the disease that is characterized by an associated risk allele in the PCDH11X gene on chromosome Xq21.3. This particular form of the disease typically has a later onset than other types and may be influenced by genetic factors as well as environmental and lifestyle factors. It is important to note that while this form of Alzheimer's may have a stronger genetic component, it is not solely determined by genetics and can still be affected by various other factors.

Alzheimer's disease type 5, also known as Alzheimer's disease, familial 5 or late-onset Alzheimer's disease is a form of the neurological disorder characterized by memory loss and cognitive decline. It is one of the most common causes of dementia in older adults. The disease typically affects individuals over the age of 65, although it can also occur in younger individuals.

Alzheimer's disease type 5 is a genetic form of the disease and is passed down through families. It is caused by mutations in one of three genes: APP, PSEN1, or PSEN2. These genes produce proteins that are involved in the formation of beta-amyloid plaques, which are a hallmark of Alzheimer's disease.

Symptoms of Alzheimer's disease type 5 may include memory loss, difficulty with language, disorientation, and changes in behavior or personality. As the disease progresses, individuals may experience further cognitive decline, problems with movement, and increased reliance on caregivers for daily tasks.

There is no cure for Alzheimer's disease type 5, but there are treatments available that can help to manage symptoms and improve quality of life for those affected by the disease. These treatments may include medications to alleviate memory loss and other cognitive functions, as well as behavioral interventions and support for caregivers.

Alzheimer's disease 8 (AD8) is a subtype of Alzheimer's disease that is characterized by genetic variation in the region 20p12.2-q11.21. It is also known as Alzheimer disease 8, familial 8 or late onset Alzheimer's disease.

Alzheimer's disease 3, also known as Alzheimer's disease type 3 or AD3, is a subtype of the neurodegenerative disorder Alzheimer's disease. Researchers continue to study AD3 to better understand its underlying mechanisms and potential treatments. Early diagnosis and intervention can be crucial in managing the symptoms and slowing down the progression of this debilitating disease.

Alzheimer's disease 10, also known as AD10, is a type of Alzheimer's disease that is characterized by a variation in the region 7q36. The symptoms of AD10 tend to appear earlier in life than other forms of Alzheimer's disease, and may include memory loss, difficulty with language, and changes in behavior and mood. Alzheimer's disease 11, also known as late-onset Alzheimer's, is a type of Alzheimer's disease that affects individuals over the age of 65. It is characterized by memory loss and cognitive decline, and is linked to genetic variations in the region 9p22.1 on chromosome 9.

Alzheimer's disease 15, also known as AD15, is a subtype of Alzheimer's disease that is characterized by a variant in the region 3q22-q24. It is referred to as late onset Alzheimer's disease because it typically presents later in life compared to other types of Alzheimer's disease.

Alzheimer's disease 17, also known as AD17 or Alzheimer disease 17, is a type of Alzheimer's disease characterized by mutations in the TREM2 gene. It is sometimes referred to as late-onset Alzheimer's disease due to its association with older age.

Alzheimer's disease 18, also known as AD18 or Alzheimer disease 18, is a type of Alzheimer's disease that has a material basis in a mutation in the ADAM10 gene on chromosome 15q21. It can also be referred to as Alzheimer's disease, late-onset. The term "late-onset" indicates that the onset of symptoms typically occurs after the age of 65. Alzheimer's disease 19 (AD19) is a subtype of Alzheimer's disease characterized by the presence of specific variants in the gene for phospholipase D3 (PLD3). It is also known as late-onset Alzheimer's disease.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1b is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by the presence of hypoplastic or underdeveloped tooth enamel. This condition can be caused by mutations in the ENAM gene, which is located on chromosome 4q13. It is also known as AI1B and has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the enamelin gene (ENAM). The exact synonyms for this condition include amelogenesis imperfecta type IB, autosomal dominant hypoplastic local amelogenesis imperfecta, and hereditary localized enamel hypoplasia.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 4, also known as AI4 or AIHHT, is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the production of malformed and poorly mineralized dentin. This condition can affect both primary and permanent teeth, leading to discoloration, pitting, and other visible cosmetic issues.
Amelogenesis imperfecta type 4 occurs when there is a mutation in the DLX3 gene, which plays a crucial role in tooth development. The term "hypomaturation-hypoplastic" refers to the underdevelopment of both the enamel and dentin layers of the teeth. In some cases, this condition can also lead to taurodontism, where the pulp chamber is wider than usual due to the presence of malformed roots.
While there is no cure for Amelogenesis imperfecta type 4, proper dental care and management can help alleviate its symptoms and prevent further complications. Regular dental checkups are essential in monitoring the condition and ensuring that any necessary treatments are provided promptly.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1a is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the tooth enamel formation. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the beta-3 laminin gene (LAMB3) on chromosome 1q32. The condition is characterized by hypoplastic or underdeveloped enamel, leading to defective tooth structure and function. This type of amelogenesis imperfecta has an exact synonym AI1A and is also known as amelogenesis imperfecta hypoplastic type IA and amelogenesis imperfecta type IA.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 3a is a type of autosomal dominant disease, characterized by the failure to produce normal enamel in the teeth. It is caused by mutations in the FAM83H gene, which is located on chromosome 8q24. This condition has been referred to as amelogenesis imperfecta type III and autosomal dominant amelogenesis imperfecta hypocalcification type.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1c is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the tooth enamel production. It is caused by mutations in the ENAM gene, which encodes for the protein enamelin, an essential component of tooth enamel. The condition can result in hypoplastic or locally hypoplastic tooth enamel, often leading to openbite and malocclusion. The exact synonyms for this condition include AI1C, amelogenesis imperfecta type IC, autosomal recessive amelogenesis imperfecta, and autosomal recessive amelogenesis imperfecta local hypoplastic type.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 2a1 is a specific subtype of Amelogenesis Imperfecta, which is a condition characterized by the production of abnormal or incomplete enamel. It is caused by mutations in the KLK4 gene on chromosome 19q13, and it has been assigned the synonym AI2A1. This type of Amelogenesis Imperfecta is characterized by pigmented hypomaturation, which means that the enamel does not develop properly due to a lack of melanin production.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1e is a form of X-linked dominant disorder. It is also known as AIH1 and has a material basis in an X-linked dominant mutation of the gene encoding amelogenin (AMELX). It can be characterized by hypoplastic/hypomaturation of teeth, with snow-capped appearance, and is related to X-linked enamel hypoplasia.

X-linked amelogenesis imperfecta, hypoplastic type 2 (AIH3) is a genetic disorder that affects tooth development. It is caused by mutations in the Xq22-q28 region and results in an abnormality in tooth enamel formation. This condition can lead to defective tooth development, including smaller or irregularly shaped teeth, and can also cause sensitivity to temperature. Treatment options for AIH3 may include dental care and preventative measures, such as avoiding extreme hot or cold temperatures that could exacerbate the condition.

amelogenesis imperfecta hypomaturation type 2a2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the development of teeth. Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1g is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of teeth. The disorder results in defective enamel formation, leading to hypoplastic or malformed teeth.

In addition to affecting dental development, Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1g has also been associated with other health issues such as nephrocalcinosis and gingival fibromatosis. Nephrocalcinosis is a condition characterized by the deposition of calcium deposits in the renal tubules, which can lead to kidney stones and impaired kidney function. Gingival fibromatosis is a benign tumor that grows on the gums, causing swelling and discomfort.

It's important to note that Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1g is rare and affects only a small number of individuals. However, if you suspect that you or a family member may be affected by this condition, it's crucial to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy 1 (ATD1) is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by the presence of multiple ribs, known as short rib-thoracic dysplasia. Atrial heart septal defect 1 (ASD1) is a type of atrial heart septal defect that occurs when there is a hole in the interatrial septum, which is the wall separating the two chambers of the heart. This condition can cause problems with blood flow and can lead to complications such as arrhythmias or heart failure if left untreated. Treatment options for ASD1 may include surgery, catheter-based procedures, or medications to manage symptoms. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and management of this condition.

Atrial heart septal defect 2 (ASD2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease. This condition can lead to various complications and may require medical intervention to manage symptoms and improve heart function.
ASD2 results from mutations in the GATA4 gene located on chromosome 8p23. The exact synonym for ASD2 is atrial septal defect 2 (ASD2).

Atrial heart septal defect 3, also known as ASD3 or atrial septal defect type 3, is a condition where there is a hole in the wall (septum) that separates the two upper chambers of the heart. This hole can cause blood to leak from the right side of the heart into the lungs, which can lead to shortness of breath and fatigue. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the MYH6 gene on chromosome 14q12.

Atrial septal defect 4, also known as ASD4 and atrial heart septal defect 4, is a type of congenital heart defect that occurs when the wall separating the two chambers of the heart (the atria) does not develop properly. This condition causes blood to flow from the left atrium to the right atrium, which can lead to increased blood volume in the left side of the heart and may cause problems with the lungs, heart valves, or other organs. Atrial septal defect 4 is often diagnosed with a physical examination, chest X-ray, echocardiogram, or electrocardiogram. Treatment options for atrial septal defect 4 depend on the severity of the condition and may include medications, surgery, or catheter-based procedures to close the hole in the heart.

Atrial Heart Septal Defect 5 (ASD5) is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It's an atrial heart septal defect, which means it affects the structure and function of the heart. Specifically, ASD5 has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ACTC1 gene on chromosome 15q14.

Autoimmune lymphoproliferative syndrome type 2a is a rare genetic disorder that affects the immune system. It is caused by mutations in the CASP10 gene, which leads to the overproduction of proteases and other inflammatory molecules. This can cause symptoms such as fever, abdominal pain, diarrhea, skin rashes, joint pain, and swelling. In some cases, it can also affect the brain and cause neurological symptoms. Leber Congenital Amaurosis 16 (LCA16) is a genetic disorder that affects the retina, which is the part of the eye responsible for vision. It is caused by mutations in the KCNJ13 gene on chromosome 2q37. LCA16 is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that to have full expression of the disorder, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent).
LCA16 typically presents in early childhood with symptoms such as severe night blindness, poor vision, and difficulty seeing colors. The disease progressively worsens over time, leading to complete loss of vision by the teenage years or early adulthood. There is no cure for LCA16, but treatment options may include glasses, low vision aids, and other assistive devices to help individuals manage their vision loss.
