Cataract 16 multiple types is a type of cataract.
Cataract 16 multiple types has definition A cataract that has_material_basis_in heterozygous or homozygous mutation in the CRYAB gene on chromosome 11q..
Cataract 16 multiple types has exact synonym CTRCT16.
Cataract 16 multiple types has narrow synonym CTPP2.
Cataract 16 multiple types has narrow synonym posterior polar cataract 2.

Cataract 15 Multiple Types is a type of cataract that is caused by a genetic mutation in the MIP gene. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that if one parent has the gene mutation, there is a chance that their child will inherit it and develop the condition as well. The exact synonym for this condition is CTRCT15.

cataract 37 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.
Cataract 37 refers to the presence of a cataract in at least one eye, with an increased likelihood of inheritance due to genetic factors. This condition has been linked to variations in the region 12q24.2-q24.3 on the short arm of chromosome 12.
Cataract 37 is also known by its narrow synonyms, such as congenital cataract cerulean type 5 and CCA5. It is important to note that while there may be a genetic basis for this condition, it does not necessarily guarantee inheritance or expression in future generations.

Cataract 14 multiple types is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the presence of cataracts in individuals who have inherited a mutated copy of the GJA3 gene on chromosome 13q12. The condition has narrow synonyms such as zonular pulverulent cataract 3, and it is defined as a cataract that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the GJA3 gene.

Cataract 25 is a type of cataract that has a material basis in variation in the region 15q21-q22. It can also be referred to as CCSSO, CTRCT25, central pouch-like cataract with sutural opacities, central saccular cataract with sutural opacities, or early-onset cataract with Y-shaped suture opacities.

The term "cataract 5 multiple types" refers to a type of cataract that has a genetic basis and is passed down through families. It is caused by mutations in the HSF4 gene on chromosome 16q22, which encodes a heat-shock transcription factor. This condition can lead to vision loss if left untreated.

Cataract 21 multiple types is a genetic disorder that affects the eye and can cause blindness if left untreated. It is caused by mutations in the MAF gene on chromosome 16q23 and can be inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. The disorder typically presents with congenital cataracts, which are cloudy areas in the lens of the eye that cause vision problems. In some cases, there may also be a microcornea, or small cornea, present. Treatment for this condition usually involves surgery to remove the cataract and restore vision.

Cataract 24 is a type of autosomal dominant disease. This means that it can be passed down through generations of a family and affect different members of the family. It is characterized by the formation of cataracts, which are cloudy areas in the lens of the eye. Cataract 24 specifically refers to a cataract that has a material basis in variation in the region 17p13. This type of cataract can be inherited from a parent who carries the gene for this condition.

cataract 10 multiple types is a type of cataract that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by the presence of sutural opacities. It is also known as congenital zonular cataract with sutural opacities (CCZS) and can be caused by heterozygous mutation in the CRYBA1 gene on chromosome 17q11.

Cataract 43 is a type of autosomal dominant cataract. Cataracts are a group of eye conditions that cause cloudy or opaque vision. They can affect one or both eyes and can lead to blindness if not treated properly. In the case of Cataract 43, it has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the UNC45B gene on chromosome 17q12. This type of cataract is also known as CTRCT43.

Cataract 7 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the eyesight, specifically the lens of the eye. It is caused by a variation in the region 17q24 and has narrow synonyms such as CTRCT7, CCA1, Cerulean type cataract 7, and congenital Cerulean type cataract 1. The disease can cause cataracts to form, which can lead to vision loss if not treated properly.

Cataract 35 is a type of autosomal recessive disease. Cataract 35 is a type of cataract that has material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Cataract 35 has definition A cataract that has_material_basis_in variation in the region 19q13.. Cataract 35 has exact synonym CATCN1. Cataract 35 has exact synonym CTRCT35. Cataract 35 has exact synonym autosomal recessive congenital nuclear cataract 1. Cataract 35 has exact synonym cataract 35, congenital nuclear.

Cataract 45 is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by the presence of opaque lens in eye, which can lead to vision loss if not treated. Cataract 45 is caused by mutation in SIPA1L3 gene located on chromosome 19q13.

Cataract 19 is a type of autosomal recessive disease.
Cataract 19 is a type of cataract.
Cataract 19 is a type of something that at least has material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.
Cataract 19 has definition A cataract that has_material_basis_in homozygous mutation in the LIM2 gene on chromosome 19q13..
Cataract 19 has exact synonym CTRCT19.

Cataract 33 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means it can be passed down through families and is caused by changes in one of the two copies of the gene responsible for eye development. Cataracts are a clouding of the natural lens in the eye, causing vision loss. The disease has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the beaded filament structural protein-1 (BFSP1) gene on chromosome 20p12. It can also be referred to as cortical cataract 33.

Cataract 31 multiple types is a type of cataract that has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance, and it has been defined as a cataract that has a heterozygous mutation in the CHMP4B gene on chromosome 20q11. The other synonyms for this condition include CTRCT31, CPP3, CTPP3, and posterior polar cataract 3. Is there anything specific you would like to know about this condition?

Cataract 9 multiple types is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is also known as CTRCT9 and can be associated with microcornea. This condition has a genetic basis, specifically due to mutations in the CRYAA gene on chromosome 21q22. The alpha-A-crystallin protein encoded by this gene plays a crucial role in maintaining the transparency of the eye lens. When there is a mutation in this gene, it can lead to the formation of cataracts.

Cataract 44 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that refers to a cataract that has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the LSS gene on chromosome 21q22. It also has an exact synonym, CTRCT44, and another one, total early-onset cataract.

Cataract 22 Multiple Types is a type of cataract that has a material basis in heterozygous or homozygous mutation in the beta-B3 crystallin gene (CRYBB3) on chromosome 22q11. It can be inherited in an autosomal dominant or recessive manner. The condition is characterized by the formation of cataracts, which are cloudy areas in the lens of the eye that affect vision.

Cataract 3 Multiple Types, also known as CTRCT3, is a type of cataract that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the beta-B2-crystallin gene (CRYBB2) on chromosome 22q11. The term "microcornea" can be associated with this condition, and it may also be referred to as CCA2 or congenital Cerulean type cataract 2.

Cataract 17 Multiple Types is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the presence of multiple types of cataracts in individuals with one or two copies of a mutated gene. It has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and is caused by heterozygous or homozygous mutation in the beta-B1 crystallin gene (CRYBB1) on chromosome 22q12. It has exact synonym CTRCT17, and narrow synonyms include autosomal recessive congenital nuclear cataract 3 (CATCN3) or Cataract 17 Multiple Types (narrow).

Cataract 23 is a specific type of cataract characterized by a mutation in the beta-A4 crystallin gene (CRYBA4) located on chromosome 22q12. It is also known as lamellar cataract 23, and has an exact synonym of CTRCT23.

Cataract 40, also known as congenital cataract, is a genetic disorder that affects the eye and causes cloudiness in the normally clear lens of the eye. It is an X-linked monogenic disease, which means it is inherited from one parent and can cause various problems with vision. The condition is caused by mutations in the NHS gene, located on the X chromosome at position 22. There are no specific symptoms for Cataract 40, but it can result in vision loss if not treated properly.

Autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy (ADLGMD) is a type of limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by progressive muscle weakness and wasting, primarily affecting the muscles in the arms, legs, and pelvic region.

Autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy (AR-LGMD) is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles of the arms, legs, and pelvic region. It is one of several types of limb-girdle muscular dystrophy, which refers to a group of genetic disorders that primarily affect the muscles of the shoulders, arms, legs, and hips.
AR-LGMD is caused by mutations in one of several genes located on the autosomal chromosome (chromosomes 3, 6, 9 or 12). These genes provide instructions for making proteins that are essential for muscle function. When these proteins are missing or do not work properly, it can lead to weakness and wasting of the muscles over time.
Symptoms of AR-LGMD can vary widely depending on which specific gene is affected and which muscle groups are involved. Common symptoms may include weakness in the hip, thigh, or shoulder muscles; difficulty walking; and foot deformities such as pes planus (flatfoot). Some people with AR-LGMD may also experience heart problems or other health issues related to the muscles.
There is no cure for AR-LGMD, but treatments are available to help manage symptoms and improve quality of life. These may include physical therapy, medications, orthotics (such as braces), and assistive devices like wheelchairs or walkers. It's important to work with a healthcare provider to develop an individualized treatment plan that addresses your specific needs and goals.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2a is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles of the legs, hips, pelvic area, and lower back. It is caused by mutations in the CAPN3 gene, which provides instructions for making a proteolytic enzyme called calpain-3. These mutations can lead to the production of an abnormal or less active form of this enzyme, which can disrupt normal muscle function and cause the muscles to weaken and waste away over time. This condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2b (LGMD2B) is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles of the legs, hips, and pelvic area. It is one of nine types of autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophies (LGMDs). LGMD2B has a material basis in mutations in the DYSF gene on chromosome 2p13, which provides instructions for making a protein called dysferlin. This protein is important for maintaining the structural integrity of muscle cells. When there is a deficiency or absence of this protein, it can lead to muscle weakness and an increased risk of developing cataracts. LGMD2B has exact synonyms such as LGMD3 and limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to dysferlin deficiency. It is important to note that the condition can be diagnosed using genetic testing, which can help identify the specific mutation in the DYSF gene.

text: autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2c is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles. It is caused by a mutation in the SGCG gene, which is located on chromosome 13q12. This condition can cause severe muscle weakness and problems with muscle tone, particularly in the legs and arms. It typically begins in childhood and progresses rapidly, leading to significant disability within a few years. The disorder has exact synonyms such as DMDA1, LGMD2C, Maghrebian myopathy, SCARMD, autosomal recessive Duchenne-like muscular dystrophy type 1, deficiency of sarcoglycan gamma, gamma-sarcoglycanopathy, limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to gamma-sarcoglycan deficiency, and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2C. It is also known as severe childhood autosomal recessive muscular dystrophy North African type.

Autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2D, also known as alpha-sarcoglycanopathy or LGMD2D, is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles in the arms, legs, and shoulders. It is caused by mutations in the SGCA gene on chromosome 17q. This condition is characterized by progressive muscle weakness, leading to difficulty in performing daily activities such as walking or climbing stairs. There is no cure for this disease, but physical therapy and supportive care can help improve symptoms.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2E is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles of the arms, legs, shoulders, and hips. It is caused by mutations in the SGCB gene, which encodes for beta-sarcoglycan. These mutations lead to a deficiency in this protein, causing muscle weakness and progressive disability.
Type 2E is one of several subtypes of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is characterized by muscle weakness that begins in the shoulders and hips and spreads to the arms, legs, and other muscles over time. The disorder can also affect the heart and respiratory system.
There is no cure for autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2E, but treatment may include physical therapy, medications to improve muscle strength and reduce inflammation, and assistive devices such as wheelchairs or walkers.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2F, also known as LGMD2F and delta-sarcoglycanopathy, is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive muscle weakness and wasting in the legs, arms, and shoulders. It is caused by mutations in the SGCD gene, which encodes for the sarcoglycan protein complex, a critical component of the sarcolemma (the outer layer of muscle cells).
Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2F is one of over 60 subtypes of limb-girdle muscular dystrophy, which are characterized by weakness in the muscles that attach the shoulder to the torso (the shoulders) and those that stabilize the elbows and hips (the pelvic girdle).
Symptoms typically begin during childhood or adolescence and may include proximal muscle weakness, joint contractures, scapular winging, and calf hypertrophy. As the disease progresses, individuals may experience difficulty with activities of daily living, such as walking, climbing stairs, and swallowing.
There is currently no cure for autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2F, but treatments are available to help manage symptoms and improve quality of life. These may include physical therapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy, wheelchair use, and medications to alleviate pain or improve muscle function.

Autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2g is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles in the arms, legs, shoulders, and hips. It is caused by mutations in the TCAP gene, which provides instructions for making a protein called telethonin. Telethonin plays an essential role in preventing muscle damage during intense physical activity. When there is a deficiency of telethonin due to mutations in the TCAP gene, it can lead to weakness and wasting of the muscles, resulting in the characteristic features of autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2g.

This disorder is one of several types of autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophies, which are characterized by weakness and wasting of the muscles in the arms, legs, shoulders, and hips. Autosomal recessive muscle-girdle dystrophy type 2g is a specific subtype of autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has been identified. It is also known by other names such as LGMD2G, limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to telethonin deficiency, and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle type 2G.

Individuals with autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2g may experience a gradual onset of weakness and wasting in the muscles of their arms, legs, shoulders, and hips. This can lead to limited mobility, difficulty performing daily activities, and an increased risk of falls and fractures. In severe cases, it can also affect the heart and respiratory systems. There is no cure for autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2g, but treatment options may include physical therapy, medications to manage symptoms, and assistive devices to help with mobility.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2h is a type of autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy characterized by progressive muscle weakness and wasting in the arms, legs, shoulders, back, and pelvic area. It is caused by mutations in the TRIM32 gene on chromosome 9q. Other synonyms for this condition include limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to TRIM32 deficiency, muscular dystrophy Hutterite type, and sarcotubular myopathy.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2j is a condition that affects the muscles of the legs, arms, and pelvic region. It is caused by mutations in the TTN gene, which provides instructions for making a protein called titin. This protein plays an important role in maintaining the structural integrity of muscle fibers.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2j is one of several types of autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophies (LGMDs). LGMDs are genetic disorders that predominantly affect the muscles of the arms, legs, and pelvic region. They typically begin in childhood or adolescence and progress slowly over time.

There is no cure for autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2j, but treatment may include physical therapy to improve strength and mobility, medications to manage symptoms, and assistive devices such as wheelchairs or walkers. Genetic counseling is also recommended for families affected by this condition.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2l is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles in the arms, legs, hips, and pelvic region. It is one of nine types of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. This specific type is characterized by muscle weakness and was first described by Dr. L. G. M. de Konings in 1963. It is caused by mutations in the ANO5 gene on chromosome 11p14, which provides instructions for making a protein called ankyrin-binding protein 1. This protein is important for maintaining the structure of muscle cells and is often affected in people with this type of dystrophy. It can cause significant disability and affects about 1 in every 800 to 1,200 individuals worldwide.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2q is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles in the arms, legs, shoulders, and hips. It is caused by a mutation in the PLEC1 gene, which provides instructions for making a protein called plectin. This protein plays an important role in maintaining the structure of muscle fibers, and when it isn't working properly, it can lead to weakness and muscle breakdown.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2q is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. It can affect people of all ages, but it often becomes more noticeable during adolescence or adulthood.

There is no cure for autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2q, but treatment may include physical therapy, medications to manage symptoms, and supportive care.

Autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2s, also known as LGMD2S, is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive muscle weakness and wasting in the arms, legs, shoulders, hips, and pelvic region. It is caused by a mutation in the TRAPPC11 gene on chromosome 4q35. Symptoms typically begin during childhood or adolescence and worsen over time. There is no cure for this condition, but physical therapy, assistive devices, and medications can help manage symptoms.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2W, also known as LGMD2W, is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive muscle weakness and wasting in the legs, arms, and other muscles. It is caused by mutations in the LIM zinc finger domain containing 2 gene (LIMS2) located on chromosome 2q14. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that to develop the disease, a person must have two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. Symptoms typically appear during childhood or adolescence and worsen over time. There is no cure for LGMD2W, but physical therapy, occupational therapy, and medications can help manage symptoms.

autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2y is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy characterized by progressive weakness and stiffening in the legs, hips, and spine. It is caused by mutations in the TOR1AIP1 gene on chromosome 1q24. The condition is also known as LGMD2Y and can be caused by a deficiency of the protein Torsin-1A-interacting protein 1. Additionally, it can cause muscular dystrophy with progressive weakness, distal contractures and rigid spine or muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2Y.

Autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2X, also known as LGMD2X, is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles in the arms and legs. It is caused by mutations in the BVES gene on chromosome 6q21. The symptoms of this condition typically begin in childhood or adolescence and can worsen over time. Weakness of the muscles in the arms, legs, and pelvic region are common features of LGMD2X. In some cases, it can also affect the heart and other organs. There is no cure for this condition, but treatment options may include physical therapy, medications to manage symptoms, and assistive devices to help with daily activities.

Leber congenital amaurosis 10 (LCA10) is a type of monogenic disease. It is characterized by severe infantile-onset cone-rod dystrophy with high hyperopia and severe ERG abnormalities, and has a material basis in mutation in the CEP290 gene on chromosome 12q21.32. This condition is also known as LCA10.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2O, also known as LGMD2O and MDDGC3, is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive weakness and wasting of the muscles in the arms, legs, shoulders, and hips. It is caused by mutations in the POMGNT1 gene located on chromosome 1p34. This condition is one of several types of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy, which affects the muscles that attach the ribcage to the spine and help with movement. Symptoms typically begin in childhood or adolescence and progress over time. There is no cure for this condition, but treatment may include physical therapy, medications to manage symptoms, and assistive devices to improve mobility.

autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2p is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy.
autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2p has definition An autosomal recessive disorder that results from mutations in the DAG1 gene on chromosome 3p21., which leads to a deficiency of alpha-dystroglycan.
autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2p has exact synonym LGMD2P.
autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2p has exact synonym MDDGC9.
autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2p has exact synonym muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C9.
autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2p has exact synonym muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy limb-girdle DAG1-related.<|endoftext|>

Autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2 (LGMD2T) is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive muscle weakness and wasting in the arms, legs, neck, and pelvic area. It is caused by mutations in the GMPPB gene on chromosome 3p21. This condition affects both males and females equally and typically presents in childhood or adolescence. The symptoms can include muscle weakness, joint pain, and limited mobility. There is no cure for this condition, but physical therapy, medications, and assistive devices may help manage the symptoms.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2u is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy.
Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2u is caused by homozygous mutation in the ISPD gene on chromosome 7p21.
It has exact synonyms as LGMD2U, MDDGC7, autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to ISPD deficiency, muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 2U and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C7.

autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2m is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy that is caused by mutations in the gene encoding fukutin (FKTN) on chromosome 9q31.

autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2k is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy.
Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2k has a definition as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding protein O-mannosyltransferase (POMT1).
Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2k has exact synonyms such as LGMD2K, MDDGC1, limb-girdle muscular dystrophy-intellectual disability syndrome, and muscular dystrophy type 2K. It also has the synonym muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C 1.

autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2n is a condition that affects the muscles in the arms, legs, and hips. It is caused by mutations in the POMT2 gene, which is located on chromosome 14q24.3.

Autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2i is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles in the arms and legs. It is caused by mutations in the gene that codes for fukutin-related protein (FKRP). These mutations can cause a deficiency of this protein, which is important for the proper functioning of the muscles.

Autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2i typically begins in childhood and progresses slowly over time. It can lead to muscle weakness, pain, and limited mobility. In some cases, it can also affect the heart and other organs.

There is no cure for autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2i, but there are treatments available to help manage the symptoms. These may include physical therapy, medications to manage pain and inflammation, and assistive devices such as wheelchairs or walkers.

It is important for people with this condition to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop an individualized treatment plan that addresses their specific needs and goals.

Autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 1H (LGMD1H) is a form of autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy characterized by weakness and wasting of muscles in the arms, legs, shoulders, and hips. It is caused by mutations in the Laminin alpha 2 (LAMA2) gene, which provides instructions for making a protein called laminin-210. This protein plays a crucial role in maintaining the structure of the extracellular matrix and is essential for proper muscle function. When the LAMA2 gene is mutated, it leads to the production of an abnormal or missing laminin-210 protein, which can cause muscle weakness and other symptoms associated with LGMD1H.
Autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 1H primarily affects the muscles in the legs, hips, shoulders, and arms, causing weakness and wasting over time. Other potential symptoms include joint pain, contractions or tightness of the muscles (myotonia), and limited mobility. The severity of the condition can vary widely among affected individuals, with some experiencing mild symptoms while others have severe disability.
There is no cure for autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 1H at present, but treatment options may include physical therapy, medications to manage symptoms, and assistance with mobility devices or wheelchair use. In some cases, gene therapy may also be considered as a potential treatment option for LGMD1H.

autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2 is a type of autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that results from a mutation in the TNPO3 gene on chromosome 7q32. It has the exact synonyms LGMD1F, autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 1F, and muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 1F.

Autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 1 is a form of autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy, characterized by progressive muscle weakness and wasting in the shoulders, arms, legs, and pelvic area. The condition is caused by a mutation in the DNAJB6 gene located on chromosome 7q36. This form of the disease has the exact synonyms LGMD1D, autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 1E, and muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 1D.

autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 3 is a condition that affects the muscles in the arms, legs, shoulders, and pelvic region. It is caused by mutations in the HNRNPDL gene on chromosome 4q21. The symptoms usually begin during childhood or adolescence and progress slowly over time. There are no specific treatments available for this condition, but physical therapy, medication, and assistive devices can help manage the symptoms.

hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 1 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MYH7 gene on chromosome 14q12. It can also be referred to as CMH1, cardiomyopathy, familial hypertrophic 1, and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 19.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 2, also known as CMH2, is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has material basis in heterozygous mutation in the cardiac troponin-T2 gene (TNNT2). This condition affects the heart muscle, causing it to become thick and difficult for the heart to pump blood effectively. It can lead to shortness of breath, chest pain, and even heart failure in severe cases. Treatment typically involves medications to manage symptoms and reduce the workload on the heart, as well as lifestyle changes such as exercise and diet modification. Surgical intervention may also be necessary in some cases.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 3, also known as CMH3, is a form of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM). HCM is a genetic heart condition characterized by the thickening and stiffening of the heart muscle. It can lead to reduced blood flow out of the heart, making it harder for the heart to pump blood effectively.

HCM can be caused by mutations in any one of several genes, including those that encode proteins involved in sarcomere function (such as TPM1 and DHPS), or those that regulate calcium ion movement (such as CAV3). In the case of HCM3, specifically, it is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the alpha-tropomyosin gene (TPM1) on chromosome 15q22.

There are different types of HCM, based on which genes have been affected and which proteins are involved. In addition to HCM3, some common examples include HCM1 (caused by mutations in the DHPS gene), HCM2 (caused by mutations in the beta-myosin heavy chain gene), and HCM4 (caused by mutations in the sarcosin gene).

It's important to note that not everyone with a diagnosis of HCM will experience the same symptoms or require the same treatment. Some people may have mild symptoms that can be managed with lifestyle changes, such as exercise and dietary restrictions, while others may have more severe symptoms that require medication or even surgery.

If you've been diagnosed with HCM3, it's crucial to work closely with your healthcare provider to develop an individualized treatment plan based on your specific needs and medical history.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 4, also known as CMH4 or familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy type 4, is a subtype of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy characterized by mutations in the MYBPC3 gene on chromosome 11p11. It is one of several types of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which are inherited forms of the disease that can cause thickening and stiffening of the heart muscle. In addition to myocytes in the left ventricle, mutations in MYBPC3 have also been found in atria and other non-myocyte cells within the heart.
